  "prompt": "Can Indians work for NASA?",
  "response": "Yes, Indians can work for **NASA** (National Aeronautics and Space Administration) under certain conditions. Here are the key factors to consider:\n\n1. **Citizenship Requirement**:  \n   Most positions at NASA require **U.S. citizenship** due to the sensitive and classified nature of the work, especially for roles involving technology, research, and space exploration. This is governed by U.S. federal regulations and security clearances.\n\n2. **Non-U.S. Citizens Opportunities**:  \n   - **International Collaborations**: NASA collaborates with international space agencies, including ISRO (Indian Space Research Organisation). Indian scientists and researchers can work with NASA through these partnerships or joint missions.  \n   - **Visiting Scientists/Researchers**: Indians can participate in NASA programs as visiting scientists, researchers, or students under specific agreements or fellowships.  \n   - **Contractors or Universities**: Some NASA projects are outsourced to private companies or universities, where non-U.S. citizens may be employed.  \n\n3. **Pathways to Employment**:  \n   - **Acquiring U.S. Citizenship**: Indians who become U.S. citizens can apply for NASA jobs.  \n   - **Education and Expertise**: NASA often recruits highly skilled individuals with advanced degrees in STEM fields (Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics). Indians with strong academic and professional backgrounds can position themselves as competitive candidates.  \n   - **Internships and Fellowships**: NASA offers internships and fellowships for students, some of which may be open to non-U.S. citizens.  \n\n4. **Examples of Indians at NASA**:  \n   Several Indian-origin scientists and engineers have worked or are currently working at NASA, including **Dr. Kamlesh Lulla** (Chief Scientist for Earth Observing Systems) and **Dr. Swati Mohan** (Lead Guidance & Controls Engineer for the Mars Perseverance Rover mission).  \n\nIn summary, while direct employment at NASA typically requires U.S. citizenship, Indians can engage with NASA through international collaborations, research opportunities, and academic programs.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
